Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Cooperative Bank of Kenya; Jubilee

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-08-03T15:39:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-03/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-cooperative-bank-of-kenya-jubilee.html
Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
slumped for a seventh day, the longest losing streak since the
seven days through Feb. 18, 2009, weakening 2.7 percent to
797.97 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, the lowest close since
Oct. 4, 2010.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index slid for the second day, weakening
0.5 percent to 2,023.13 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis ,
the lowest close since April 7. Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped
three days of gains, falling 0.1 percent to 66.29 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index
declined for a second day, losing 0.2 percent to 23,808.68 by
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the
bourse’s website. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index rose
for a second day, advancing 0.2 percent to 1,174.71 by the 3
p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.        Barclays Bank of Kenya Ltd. (BCBL)  , the East African
nation’s second-largest lender by market value, declined 5
cents, or 0.3 percent, to 15.4 shillings, the lowest close since
April 6. The Nairobi-based bank posted a 2.2 percent drop in
first-half profit to 3.64 billion shillings ($40 million).  Cooperative Bank of Kenya Ltd. (COOP KN), the East African
nation’s fifth-largest lender, gained 15 cents, or 1 percent, to
15.15 shillings, after it forecast that profit will rise by 42
percent this year to 6.5 billion shillings, supported by credit
growth.  Jubilee Holdings Ltd. (JBIC)  , a Kenyan insurer, rose 2
shillings, or 1.1 percent, to 181 shillings, the highest close
since June 21. The Nairobi-based company said its first-half
profit through June increased by 35 percent to 781 million
shillings, according to an e-mailed statement today.  National Bank of Kenya Ltd. (NBKL)  , a state-owned
lender, slipped 50 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 28.75 shillings,
the first decline in three days, after profit slumped 22 percent
to 640.3 million shillings in the first half through June
compared with a year earlier.  Presco Plc (PRESCO)  , a Nigerian palm-oil producer,
advanced 37 kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 7.87 naira, the highest
close since July 19. Net income more than doubled to 1.5 billion
naira ($9.8 million) in the first half compared with 718 million
naira a year earlier, according to  Renaissance Capital .  To contact the reporter on this story:
